abstract: Hereâ€™s our exhaustive new-show roundup of a very crowded season.
snippet: Hereâ€™s our exhaustive new-show roundup of a very crowded season.
lead_paragraph: There may never have been a fall television season as jam packed as the one weâ€™re about to endure. New titans are arriving, dropping their generously financed catalogs into an already saturated market. The new wave of potential Netflix killers begins with the arrivals of the Apple TV Plus and Disney Plus streaming services on Nov. 1 and Nov. 12, each debuting with a small but buzzy roster of original series.

abstract: Mark your calendar. From a revamped MoMA and the fearless Pope.L to Renaissance sculptors and female modernists, here are more than 100 shows that define the new season.
snippet: Mark your calendar. From a revamped MoMA and the fearless Pope.L to Renaissance sculptors and female modernists, here are more than 100 shows that define the new season.
lead_paragraph: Itâ€™s a season of debuts for artists â€” from Renaissance masters never before seen in New York to jazz pianists with breakout museum shows â€” and also for real estate. In addition to the Lower Manhattan Cultural Councilâ€™s 40,000-square-foot arts center at Governors Island and Pace Galleryâ€™s new flagship tower in Chelsea, both slated to open in September, the Museum of Modern Art reopens after an extensive renovation and expansion on Oct. 21. Youâ€™ll find these highlights, and more than 100 others, below, including watercolors, pastels, immigrant stories, fairs and a full year of women-centered art shows in Baltimore.

abstract: In a meme group, sardonic and sincere Williamson supporters unite against the haters.
snippet: In a meme group, sardonic and sincere Williamson supporters unite against the haters.
lead_paragraph: It began, like so many modern presidential campaign stories do, as a joke. Sarah Marilyn, a 28-year-old Brooklyn social media strategist, didnâ€™t bother to watch the first Democratic debates in June. She was only vaguely aware that they were happening until the memes began cascading onto her phone. She chased the best jokes, fell into a kind of Photoshop fugue state, and emerged as the co-founder of a Facebook page dedicated to the candidate with the most stimulating content: Marianne Williamsonâ€™s Dank Meme Stash.
